dove.util.struct.tree

Class Tree<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • dove.util.struct.tree.Tree<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - typeparameter for the content of this treeelement
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable<Tree<T>>, java.lang.Iterable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    M2Tree, StringMap, TreeMap

    public class Tree<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<Tree<T>>, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable, java.lang.Cloneable
    provides a tree-structure for collecting and storing data Notes:
    • this class CAN be threadsafe, if specified. if this tree is not made threadsafe, accessing this tree within multiple threads will result in severe errors and a possible damage/loss of data contained in this tree even if this tree is made threadsafe, the results will highly vary upon the timing in executing the single tasks
    • Typesafety is always guaranteed due to clazz.
    • If you intend to override this class, the following methods are usefull to override in order to create a more specific behaviour:
    See Also:
    nodeCopy(), aswell, all methods provided MUST provide the option to be threadsafe, Tree.TreeScheduler, Tree.TreeOp, runOp(dove.util.treelib.Tree.TreeOp<R>, dove.util.treelib.Tree.TreeTask.TaskOpType), further more, all structural operations (adding/re-/moving) nodes, have to take treeglobal objects into account, like the TreeScheduler, the IDGiver, etc., WARNING: if a subclass of Tree uses an operation provided by this class, the method named _*method_name* MUST ALWAYS be used to avoid deadlocks in the scheduler example: ..., Serialized Form

      • goThroughTree

        protected void goThroughTree(Tree<T> startNode,
                             Tree.GoThroughManager<? extends Tree<T>> mgr)
        goes through this subtree (with startNode as root) inorder rules for running through the tree:
        • 1. if the algorithm can go one level deeper it will go one level deeper
        • 2. if the algorithm can't go any deeper on it's current path, it will go on with the next child of this node's parent
        • 3. if all nodes on a level with the same parent are processed, the algorithm steps one level back
        • 4. if mgr.breakOff() returns true, the algorithm will break off
        Parameters:
        startNode - the root of the subtree to analyse
        mgr - the manager defining the go through conditions
        See Also:
        Tree.GoThroughManager
